-- §9. Betti number rigidity
-- Every smooth quintic threefold in ℙ⁴ has h²·²(X) = 1.
-- The Betti numbers are topological invariants: b₀=1, b₂=1, b₃=204, b₄=1, b₆=1.
-- Extra H²·² classes CANNOT appear by deformation — this requires singular transitions.
-- Correction of a common misconception: the "new" Hodge classes at special points
-- arise from conifold transitions (topology change), not smooth deformation.

-- h^{1,1} = 1, h^{2,2} = 1 for ALL smooth quintic 3-folds
-- The single H^{2,2} class is the hyperplane-squared class H² ∈ H⁴(X, ℤ)
-- The Hodge Conjecture for H^{2,2} of a smooth quintic is therefore trivially true:
-- every H^{2,2} class is a rational multiple of H².

-- The INTERESTING Hodge problem for CY3 is in H³ (the middle cohomology).
